abstract: U.S. political campaigns should make someone in their teams responsible for monitoring online disinformation about their candidate ahead of the 2020 elections, the Democratic National Committee (DNC) said on Monday.
snippet: U.S. political campaigns should make someone in their teams responsible for monitoring online disinformation about their candidate ahead of the 2020 elections, the Democratic National Committee (DNC) said on Monday.
lead_paragraph: (Reuters) - U.S. political campaigns should make someone in their teams responsible for monitoring online disinformation about their candidate ahead of the 2020 elections, the Democratic National Committee (DNC) said on Monday.
headline_main: Democrats Release Tips for Election Campaigns to Fight Online Disinformation
headline_print_headline: Democrats Release Tips for Election Campaigns to Fight Online Disinformation

abstract: Arsenal's decision to distance the club from midfielder Mesut Ozil's criticism of China's policy towards its Muslim Uighur minority won't surprise anyone familiar with the scramble by Europe's soccer powers for a slice of the expanding Chinese market.

headline_main: Clubs Unlikely to Bite the Chinese Hand That Feeds

abstract: The child tax credit, begun in 1997 as a tax cut, has become an anti-poverty program. But more than a third of children don’t receive it because their parents earn too little.
snippet: The child tax credit, begun in 1997 as a tax cut, has become an anti-poverty program. But more than a third of children don’t receive it because their parents earn too little.
lead_paragraph: MONROE, La. — With two children and a third on the way, Ciera Dismuke worked five jobs last year while earning just under $15,000. Although the Trump administration often boasts that it doubled the federal child tax credit to $2,000 per child, Ms. Dismuke, like millions of Americans, earned too little to fully qualify. Instead, she got $934 a child, an increase of just $75.

abstract: U.S. diplomats who mysteriously fell ill in Cuba and China would get long-term emergency health and other benefits under a $1.4 trillion spending bill lawmakers unveiled on Monday.
snippet: U.S. diplomats who mysteriously fell ill in Cuba and China would get long-term emergency health and other benefits under a $1.4 trillion spending bill lawmakers unveiled on Monday.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. diplomats who mysteriously fell ill in Cuba and China would get long-term emergency health and other benefits under a $1.4 trillion spending bill lawmakers unveiled on Monday.

abstract: And who gets to say? As the latest list of lauded style-setters arrives, it may be time to say goodbye to the whole concept.
snippet: And who gets to say? As the latest list of lauded style-setters arrives, it may be time to say goodbye to the whole concept.
lead_paragraph: This weekend, the International Best-Dressed List was released — its 79th iteration, but the first under its new caretaker, Air Mail, the Graydon Carter newsletter/zine. Did you notice?

abstract: Chile defended itself on Monday against criticism it was too weak in presiding over international climate change negotiations, saying it did all it could but that four big polluting countries got in the way.
snippet: Chile defended itself on Monday against criticism it was too weak in presiding over international climate change negotiations, saying it did all it could but that four big polluting countries got in the way.
lead_paragraph: SANTIAGO/LONDON/MADRID — Chile defended itself on Monday against criticism it was too weak in presiding over international climate change negotiations, saying it did all it could but that four big polluting countries got in the way.
headline_main: Under Fire Over Climate Summit, Chile Blames Big Polluters
headline_print_headline: Under Fire Over Climate Summit, Chile Blames Big Polluters

abstract: Democratic Representative Elissa Slotkin, co-author of a column that helped launch the impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump, ended months of uncertainty on Monday by telling voters at a noisy town hall meeting that she will vote for impeachment.
snippet: Democratic Representative Elissa Slotkin, co-author of a column that helped launch the impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump, ended months of uncertainty on Monday by telling voters at a noisy town hall meeting that she will vote for impea...
lead_paragraph: ROCHESTER, Mich. — Democratic Representative Elissa Slotkin, co-author of a column that helped launch the impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump, ended months of uncertainty on Monday by telling voters at a noisy town hall meeting that she will vote for impeachment.
headline_main: At Noisy Town Hall, a Vulnerable U.S. Democrat Says 'Yes' to Impeaching Trump
headline_print_headline: At Noisy Town Hall, a Vulnerable U.S. Democrat Says 'Yes' to Impeaching Trump

abstract: The former Republican presidential candidate and chairwoman of Hewlett-Packard stopped short of calling for Mr. Trump’s removal from office.
snippet: The former Republican presidential candidate and chairwoman of Hewlett-Packard stopped short of calling for Mr. Trump’s removal from office.
lead_paragraph: Carly Fiorina, the former Republican presidential candidate and chairwoman of Hewlett-Packard, said Monday that she believed it was “vital” that President Trump be impeached, but left open the possibility of voting for him in the fall of 2020.

abstract: U.S. Senate Democratic leader Chuck Schumer proposed in a letter released on Sunday that at least four witnesses including acting White House Chief of Staff Mick Mulvaney and former national security adviser John Bolton be subpoenaed to testify in the expected impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. Senate Democratic leader Chuck Schumer proposed in a letter released on Sunday that at least four witnesses including acting White House Chief of Staff Mick Mulvaney and former national security adviser John Bolton be subpoenaed to testify in the expected impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.
